  "text": "Because TRPML1 acts as a Ca 2ϩ -permeable channel [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , to further evaluate the inhibitory effect of adenosine, TRPML1-4A activity was measured by a Fura-2-based Ca 2ϩ imaging assay [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Consistent with another report [CITATION_5] , activation of TRPML1-4A by ML-SA1 induced a rapid increase in Fura-2 signal followed by a quick rundown. The mechanism underlying the rundown remains unclear. To avoid the contamination of the rundown, we co-applied ML-SA1 and adenosine followed by application of ML-SA1 alone. If adenosine inhibits TRPML1, we would expect to see a smaller Ca 2ϩ signal followed by a larger one. As shown in Fig. 2 , C and D, the Fura-2 signal in cells expressing TRPML1-4A was increased by co-application of ML-SA1 (10 M) and adenosine (10 mM), presumably due to incomplete inhibition of TRPML1 by adenosine. However, a much larger response was observed when ML-SA1 (10 M) was applied alone. ML-SA1 did not reveal Fura-2 response in untransfected cells (Fig. 2 , C and D) or cells transfected with GFP alone (data not shown). These data suggest that adenosine inhibits TRPML1 activity.",
